description.plain:
Andy Shauf is a Canadian singer-songwriter and multi-instrumentalist from Regina, Saskatchewan. He is mostly self-taught musician, accessing instruments at a young age through the Radio Shack outlet run by his parents. Born to a evangelical Christian family, Shauf began playing Christian music with his family and began professionally as a drummer for a Christian pop punk band.

He started his solo career in 2006 with his Independent release “Love and the memories of It” followed by “Grandpa Songs” in 2007.  He released  his debut album, Darker Days in 2009. Shortly after, he released two EPs, Waiting for the Sun to Leave and Sam Jones Feeds His Demons, before releasing his second studio album The Bearer of Bad News in 2012, which jump-started his career as a solo artist. Shauf’s big-break came in 2016 when he released his third studio album, The Party, to critical acclaim. It featured Shauf’s most popular song to date, “The Magician”. The album was nominated for the Polaris Music Prize and received four nominations at the Juno Awards. Shauf has been noted for his practice of recording and arranging each instrument on his albums himself.

songs.title: Wendell Walker

description.plain: The narrator has a friend named Wendell Walker who hears the voice of God say the woman he is in love with is not being true to him. She is seeing another man. What he doesn’t know is that the other man is the narrator–his friend. When Wendell catches them together he prepares to shoot the narrator but is too hesitant. The narrator pushes the gun away, but while doing so, Wendell shoots his wife and kills her. Unable to live with what he has done, Wendell then shoots himself. The narrator is left in the room with two dead friends. He realizes this mess is all his fault and asks himself, “My god, my God what have I done?”

description.plain:
In “My Dear Helen”, the narrator, an elderly man, addresses his late wife, essentially catching her up on the events of his life since she passed away.

In the latter half of the song, the narrator retells the events of the previous track, “Jerry Was a Clerk”, from a different perspective.

The narrator expresses his fear that he won’t be allowed into heaven as an “accidental murderer,” drawing a parallel between this fear and a pleasant memory from he and his wife’s early relationship, in which she met him at the gates (presumably the gates of a traveling fair or something similar) to sneak him in. He warns Helen that he may need a similar type of help if she would like him to be with her in heaven someday.

description.plain:
Unreleased from Shauf. I can only gather by the groom’s name being “Sam” that this is the same Sam from the “Sam Jones Feeds His Demons” EP, released by Shauf in 2015.

I found this in a streamingcafe.net stream from september 2014. I can only assume the title of the song is “The Wedding” as that’s where this song takes place. Lyrics are all added by ear, but im pretty confident I’ve got them down.

The song is about Sam at his wedding (If it is the same Sam as mentioned above, then this would be Sam and Victoria’s wedding day). Sam from the “Sam Jones Feeds His Demons” EP had a drinking problem and was very abusive, this could very well tell the start of Sams problems and abusive relationship with Victoria.

He’s not yet had his first dance with his bride, he’s too nervous, and he’s too stubborn to force himself up, so he just sits and ignores her while he drinks while all his friends leave him at the table while they dance. He gets up off his seat, while Victoria thinks hes finally going to dance with her, he walks straight out for a smoke and leaves her to sulk.

Unreleased from Shauf. Possibly one of the songs cut from the Bearer of Bad News record, as he had written over 100 songs for the album yet narrowed it down to just 11.

I found this in a streamingcafe.net stream from september 2014. I can only assume the title of the song is “Angela”. Lyrics are all added by ear, but im pretty confident I’ve got them down.
